01:17:31.485 --> 01:17:42.178
<v Tom>Actually Rachel, one more thing before you go. I want to circle back on the API versioning strategy we briefly mentioned last month.

01:17:42.178 --> 01:17:52.871
<v Tom>With the Salesforce integration and AI features coming, we'll likely need to introduce new API endpoints. Should we plan for a major version bump?

01:17:52.871 --> 01:18:03.564
<v Rachel>Good question, Tom. What's your recommendation on the versioning approach? I know there are different schools of thought on API versioning.

01:18:03.564 --> 01:18:14.257
<v Tom>I'd recommend we continue with our current URL versioning strategy, keeping v1 stable while introducing new capabilities in v2 endpoints where needed.

01:18:14.257 --> 01:18:24.950
<v Tom>This gives us flexibility to iterate on new features without breaking existing integrations. We can gradually deprecate v1 endpoints over time.

01:18:24.950 --> 01:18:35.643
<v Dan>From a backend perspective, I agree with that approach. We've had good experience with URL versioning. It's explicit and easy for developers to understand.

01:18:35.643 --> 01:18:46.336
<v Dan>One thing to consider is how we handle shared data models. Some entities might need different representations in v1 versus v2, which adds complexity.

01:18:46.336 --> 01:18:57.029
<v Tom>That's a good point. We should establish conventions for model evolution. I'll add API versioning guidelines to the technical planning agenda.

01:18:57.029 --> 01:19:07.722
<v Mike>From a customer perspective, enterprises are sensitive to API changes. We need clear communication and migration guides whenever we introduce breaking changes.

01:19:07.722 --> 01:19:18.415
<v Mike>I'd recommend we commit to at least twelve months of support for deprecated endpoints. That gives customers reasonable time to migrate.

01:19:18.415 --> 01:19:29.108
<v Rachel>Twelve months sounds reasonable for enterprise customers. Let's document that as part of our API policy. Tom, can you draft the versioning guidelines?

01:19:29.108 --> 01:19:39.801
<v Tom>Yes, I'll have a draft ready for the Tuesday meeting. It will cover versioning strategy, deprecation policy, and migration guide templates.

01:19:39.801 --> 01:19:50.495
<v Alex>On the frontend side, we should align our SDK versioning with the API versioning. We maintain JavaScript, Python, and Go SDKs.

01:19:50.495 --> 01:20:01.188
<v Alex>When we introduce v2 API capabilities, we'll need corresponding SDK updates. We should coordinate those releases carefully.

01:20:01.188 --> 01:20:11.881
<v Tom>Agreed, Alex. The SDK updates should be part of our release checklist. We can't launch new API features without SDK support.

01:20:11.881 --> 01:20:22.574
<v Rachel>Let's make SDK compatibility a gate for API feature launches. Tom, please include that in the versioning guidelines.

01:20:22.574 --> 01:20:33.267
<v Tom>Will do. I'll document the release coordination process between API and SDKs.

01:20:33.267 --> 01:20:43.960
<v Sarah>For the mobile SDKs, we have additional considerations around app store distribution. We can't force users to update their apps immediately.

01:20:43.960 --> 01:20:54.653
<v Sarah>So our API versioning needs to support graceful degradation. Older app versions should continue to work even as we introduce new API capabilities.

01:20:54.653 --> 01:21:05.346
<v Tom>That's an important constraint. We'll design the v2 endpoints to be additive rather than replacing v1. Both versions will coexist for the foreseeable future.

01:21:05.346 --> 01:21:16.039
<v Rachel>Good discussion on API evolution. This kind of forward-thinking will help us scale smoothly as we add capabilities.

01:21:16.039 --> 01:21:26.732
<v Rachel>Now, speaking of planning ahead, I want to briefly discuss our Q2 preview. While Q1 is our focus, we should start thinking about what comes next.

01:21:26.732 --> 01:21:37.425
<v Rachel>Based on our Q1 investments, what opportunities do you see for Q2 that we should start preparing for?

