<v Dan>See everyone at the planning meeting.

01:29:27.920 --> 01:29:38.613
<v Kim>Bye all. Great discussion.

01:29:38.613 --> 01:29:49.306
<v Alex>Take care everyone.

01:29:49.306 --> 01:30:00.000
<v Rachel>Goodbye. Great meeting today everyone.
01:30:00.000 --> 01:30:10.693
<v Mike>Actually Rachel, before everyone leaves, could we have a quick follow-up on the competitive intelligence report that came in this morning? I think it's relevant to our Q1 planning.

01:30:10.693 --> 01:30:21.386
<v Rachel>Good point Mike. Everyone, if you have a few more minutes, let's discuss this. It's important context for the decisions we just made.

01:30:21.386 --> 01:30:32.079
<v Tom>I have time. What came in from the competitive analysis?

01:30:32.079 --> 01:30:42.772
<v Mike>Our primary competitor just announced they're launching an enterprise tier with SSO and advanced audit logging. This directly impacts our differentiation strategy.

01:30:42.772 --> 01:30:53.465
<v Sarah>That's significant. Do we know their pricing structure?

01:30:53.465 --> 01:31:04.158
<v Mike>Initial reports suggest they're pricing at about fifteen percent below our enterprise offering. They're clearly trying to undercut us in the market.

01:31:04.158 --> 01:31:14.851
<v Dan>From a technical perspective, SSO implementation requires significant investment. If they're launching soon, they've been working on this for months.

01:31:14.851 --> 01:31:25.544
<v Rachel>This reinforces our decision to prioritize the Salesforce integration. Enterprise customers value integrations more than price once they've made the buy decision.

01:31:25.544 --> 01:31:36.237
<v Tom>I agree. Our integration strategy creates switching costs that pure price competition can't overcome.

01:31:36.237 --> 01:31:46.930
<v Alex>Should we accelerate our own SSO roadmap? Right now it's scheduled for Q2.

01:31:46.930 --> 01:31:57.623
<v Rachel>Let's discuss. Mike, how often does SSO come up in enterprise sales conversations?

01:31:57.623 --> 01:32:08.316
<v Mike>Almost every deal. But it's rarely a deal-breaker when we explain our security architecture. Most enterprises are willing to use our authentication system once they understand it.

01:32:08.316 --> 01:32:19.009
<v Sarah>Mobile users have different expectations. They want biometric authentication and seamless login experiences. That's why we prioritized Touch ID and Face ID support.

01:32:19.009 --> 01:32:29.702
